Ophiopogon japonicus
(Thunb.) Ker-Gawl. (Asparagaceae)

is widely regarded as both a functional food and a traditional Chinese herb and is distributed throughout 
East Asia
(

). The rhizome of 

O. japonicus

, which is the herb’ s primary medicinal component, is used in treatment or prevention of lung diseases based on its traditional applications for nourishing yin and moisturizing lung tissue when used alone or in combination with other drugs (

). The most representative constituents of 

O. japonicus

are steroidal saponins, polysaccharides, and homoisoflavonoids (

). In particular, steroidal saponins, one of the quality control constituents of 

O. japonicus

, exhibit multiple pharmacological activities, such as anticancer, anti-inflammatory, antibacterial, antioxidant, antineoplastic, antitussive, and cardiovascular protective effects (

; 

); therefore, they have attracted increasing attention in phytochemistry and pharmacology.

Steroidal saponins are abundant in food and medicinal plants of families 
Dioscoreaceae
, 
Liliaceae
, and Scrophuhrhceae (

). An increasing number of steroidal saponins have been discovered, garnering interest due to their unusual structures and excellent therapeutic effects. Steroidal saponins are considered the major bioactive compounds in monocotyledon (

), with a series of biological activities such as antitumor (

), immunomodulation (

), antimicrobial (

), and cardiovascular protective activities (

). Structurally, most aglycones are polycyclic with 27 carbon atoms, possessing one spiroketal center, which connects the E and F rings (

). Bufospirostenin A, an unusual steroid and the only example of a spirostanol with A/B rings, was previously obtained from the collected gallbladders and venom of the toad 

Bufo bufo gargarizans

in 2017 (

). It has a [5-7-6-5-5-6] hexacyclic rearranged skeleton and shows inhibitory activity against Na/K ATPase (21% and 43% inhibition at 12.5 and 25.0 μM, respectively). Due to their chemical diversity and wide spectrum of biological activities, steroidal saponins are not only a class of natural product but also a natural source of therapeutic agents.

Ophiopogonol A ( 1 ), white needle crystals (MeOH), has a molecular formula of C 27 H 42 O 4 according to a positive-ion at m / z m / z 431.3172 [M+ H] + (calcd. 431.3161 for C 27 H 43 O 4 ), as indicated by HRESIMS. In the 1 H NMR spectrum, the proton resonances for four methyl proton groups at δ H 0.69 (3H, d, J = 5.4 Hz, H 3 -27), 0.94 (3H, s, H 3 -18), 1.14 (3H, d, J = 7.0 Hz, H 3 -21), and 1.35 (3H, s, H 3 -19), one olefinic proton at 5.67 (1H, brs, H-6), and oxymethylene protons at δ H 3.49 (H-26a) and 3.58 (H-26b) were observed. The 13 C NMR spectrum revealed that compound 1 had twenty-seven carbons, including a ketal moiety at δC 109.4 (C-22), two olefinic carbons at δC 145.6 (C-5) and 122.2 (C-6), and four methyl carbons at δ C 17.0 (C-18), 17.1 (C-19), 15.5 (C-21) and 17.7 (C-27). Comparison of the 1D NMR data with those of bufospirostenin A, which was obtained from the toad
Bufo bufo
gargarizans ( Tian et al., 2017 )
, indicated that 1 had the same substructure in rings A-E (including the rearranged A and B rings), but in the F ring of 1 the Δ 25,27 double bond was replaced with C-27 methyl. The assignment of 1 H and 13 C NMR data ( Table 1 ) combined with the extensive analysis of 1 H– 1 H COSY and HSQC spectra further suggested that compound 1 was a rearranged isospirostanol. The rearranged skeleton (rings A and B) was further confirmed by the 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC spectra ( Fig. 2 ). The 1 H– 1 H COSY spectrum showed proton interactions of H-1/H 2 -2, H 2 -2/H-3, H-3/H 2 -4, H-6/H 2 -7, and H 2 -7/H-8. HMBC correlations between H 2 -4/C-5, H 2 -4/C-6, H-2β/C-10, H-2α/C-5, H 3 -19/C-1 and H 3 -19/C-9 established the 5/7 ring system connected through the C-1 to C-5 bond. Additionally, the HMBC correlations between H-7/C-8, H-7/C-9, H-8/C-11, and H-9/C-11 revealed that rings B and C were connected via the C-8 to C-9 bond. The relative configuration of 1 was established based on NOESY correlations ( Fig. 3 ), 13 C NMR data, and 3 J H, H coupling values. The NOESY correlations between H-1/H-3 α and H-1/H-9 suggested that these protons were cofacial. In addition, the NOESY correlations between H-8/H 3 -19, H-8/H 3 -18, H-20/H 3 -18 and H-14/H-16 identified the trans -trans ring junction for rings B/C and C/D, and β -orientation for H-20. The R configuration of C-25 was confirmed by the downfield shift of C-23, C-24, C-25, and C-26 from 25–28 to 29–30 ppm (
). Furthermore, the characteristic chemical shift of H-26 [ δ 3.49 (1H, t, J = 10.3 Hz, H-26a) and δ 3.58 (1H, m, H-26b), Δ δ ab < 0.48 ppm] also supported the assignment of the C-25 R configuration (
). Accordingly, the structure of 1 was established to be ophiopogonol A, as shown in Fig. 1 .

Ophiopogonol B ( 2 ), white needle crystals (MeOH), HRESIMS indicated a pseudo-molecular ion at m/z 429.3017 [M-H] - (calcd. 429.3005 for C 27 H 41 O 4 ) and showed the same molecular formula (C 27 H 42 O 4 ) as that of compound 1 . The 13 C NMR spectroscopic data of 2 displayed a total of twenty-seven carbon signals, including two olefinic carbons at δ C 145.7 (C-5) and 122.4 (C-6), and a ketal carbon signal at δC 108.9 (C-22). The 1 H NMR spectrum showed presence of one olefinic proton at δC 5.68 (1H, brs, H-6) and four methyl proton groups at δ H 0.70 (3H, d, J = 5.4 Hz, H 3 -27), 1.08 (3H, s, H 3 -18), 1.13 (3H, d, J = 7.9 Hz, H 3 -21), and 1.35 (3H, s, H 3 -19). By comparing the 1D and 2D NMR spectra ( Table 1 ), it was found that compound 2 corresponded well with compound 1 , apart from significant differences in signals attributable to the E ring. Based on 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC correlations ( Fig. 2 ), compound 2 was determined to have the same planar structure as that of 1 . NOESY correlations ( Fig. 3 ) of H 3 -19/H-8, H-8/H-13 and H-14/H-16 indicated the trans -trans ring junction of rings B, C and D. However, the α -configuration of H-20 indicated by both the NOESY correlations of H-16 / H-20, H-20 / H-23 α and the chemical shift values at δC 47.3 (C-20), 12.0 (C-21), 61.4 (C-17), and 108.9 (C-22) was distinctly different from that in 1 . This change in the configuration of H-20 was also supported by the fact that the chemical shift of H-20 at a lower field than δ 2.47 indicates a cis configuration for the proton and the oxygen atom in the F ring (
). The absolute configuration of C-25 of 2 was established to be R based on the chemical shifts of C-23, C-24, C-25, C-26 and H-26 [ δ 3.62 (2H, m, H 2 -26)] in pyridine- d 5 (
;
). Therefore, compound 2 was determined to be an epimer of 1 .

Ophiopogonol D ( 4 ), white needle crystals (MeOH), displayed m / z 431.3168 [M-H] - (calcd. 431.3161 for C 27 H 43 O 4 ) in the HRESIMS spectrum. The 1 H NMR spectrum displayed the resonances of four methyl proton groups at δ H 0.69 (3H, d, J = 5.4 Hz, H 3 -27), 1.10 (3H, s, H 3 -18), 1.20 (3H, d, J = 7.0 Hz, H 3 -21), and 1.02 (3H, s, H 3 -19) and oxymethylene protons at δ H 3.53 (H 2 -26). The 13 C NMR spectroscopic data showed twenty-seven carbon signals, including a ketal signal at δC 109.9 (C-22), one oxygenated quaternary carbon at δC 87.5 (C-14), and one oxygenated methylene carbon signal at 82.4 (C-16). Unambiguous assignments for the 1 H and 13 C NMR signals ( Table 2 ) of compound 4 were achieved based on HSQC and HMBC spectroscopic data. The HMBC correlation ( Fig. 2 ) between H-9/C-6, H-8/C-6, H 3 -18/C-14, H-16/C-14, H 2 -23/C-22, and H 2 -24/C-22 permitted the determination of a spirostanol skeleton with one hydroxyl group at C-14. The deduced spirostanol skeleton resembled that of the known compound, (25 R )-spirost-5- en-3 β ,14-diol isolated from the rhizomes of
Dioscorea prazeri ( Rajaraman et al., 1975 )
, except for the disappearance of the Δ 5,6 double bond in 4 . In the NOESY spectrum ( Fig. 3 ), the correlations of H-5/H 3 -19 indicated the β -orientation of H-5, and the cis junction of ring A/B and the α -orientation of H-3 was confirmed by the NOE correlations of H-1 α /H-3 and H-1 β /H 3 -19. Furthermore, the downfield shifts of C-23/C-24/C-25/C-26 (
) and the chemical shift of H 2 -26 [ δ 3.53 (2H, m)] (
) confirmed the assignment of C-25 R configuration. Thus, compound 4 was established as (25 R )-5 β -spirostan-3 β ,14-diol, named ophiopogonol D.

