In compounds 
1
and 
2
, the A/B ring system was rearranged with a [5- 7-6-5-5-6] hexacyclic skeleton rather than the usual decalin system. The only reported spirostanol with the 5/7 system in A-B rings (bufospirostenin A) was found in the toad 

Bufo bufo
gargarizans

; no spirostanols with the 5/7 system in A-B rings have been reported in plants (

). The 5/7 ring fragment is widely found in macrocyclic diterpenoids of the family 

Euphorbiaceae (
Zhang et al., 2018
)

. By investigating the biosynthetic route of bufogargarizins A and B (

) and macrocyclic diterpenoids with the 5/7 ring fragment, it was found that the ring-opening behavior of two six-membered rings to form a twelve-membered system is an essential step for the formation of the 5/7 bicyclic skeleton (
Fig. 4 A and 4 B
) (

). In addition, most of the previously reported steroidal saponins in 
O. japonicus
are polyhydroxy in the aglycone moiety (

). It is postulated that hydroxyl groups at C-1 and C-5 are key factors that initiate the ring-opening process, and thereby the formation of the 5/7 ring fragment in 
1
and 
2
(
Fig. 4 C
). Therefore, a plausible biosynthetic pathway for ophiopogonol A (
1
) and ophiopogonol B (
2
) was deduced (
Fig. 4
). Under certain conditions, the 6-hydroxyl group is oxidized to a ketone group. After the oxygen atom of 1-hydroxyl group attacks the relatively electron-deficient carbon atom at 10-position (β- position of 6-ketone), ethylene oxide and enol intermediates are formed. The carbanion in the enol moiety then performs a nucleophilic attack on the C-1 atom, which has lower steric hindrance, and opens the ring of ethylene oxide to furnish the target compound through reduction and dehydration.

All isolated steroidal saponins were evaluated for their cytotoxic effect on human large cell lung carcinoma cells (NCI–H460). Cisplatin served as the positive control (11.6 ± 0.7 μM). Cell viability was assessed using MTT assay. Sprengerinin C (
19)
showed significant inhibitory ability with an IC 
50
value of 2.1 ± 0.8 μM (
Table 3
and 
Fig. 5 A
). The spindle-like cell morphology of NCI–H460 cells could be distinguished at a concentration of 1.0 μM (1/2 IC 
50
), and NCI–H460 cells shriveled and vanished completely at 4.0 μM (2 times IC 
50
) (
Fig. 5B
). Additionally, an AnnexinV-FITC/PI staining was utilized to detect the apoptosis ratio of NCI–H460 cells following exposure to sprengerinin C (
19
). The percentage of apoptotic cells was significantly increased 48 h after sprengerinin C (
19
) treatment (apoptotic rates of 11.68%, 16.68%, and 74.90% induced by 1.0 μM, 2.0 μM, and 4.0 μM sprengerinin C, respectively) compared to that of the control group (7.73%) (
Fig. 6 A and 6 B
). Hoechst staining experiments revealed a similar result, showing that sprengerinin C (
19
) (1.0 μM, 2.0 μM, and 4.0 μM) could induce apoptosis of NCI–H460 cells (
Fig. 6 C
). Flow cytometry analysis of the NCI–H460 cell cycle demonstrated that sprengerinin C (
19
) could induce apoptosis in NCI–H460 cells and arrest the cycle at the G2/M phase (
Fig. 7 A and 7 B
).

Optical rotations were collected using an MCP 200 polarimeter (Anton Paar GmbH, Graz, 
Austria
). Mass spectra were measured using Bruker micro TOF-Q mass spectrometer. The 1D NMR and 2D NMR spectra were obtained using Bruker AVANCE III HD 400 MHz and 600 MHz instruments (Bruker, 
Switzerland
) with tetramethylsilane (TMS) as the internal standard. HPLC separations were carried out with a YMCpack Prep-ODS column (250 ✕ 
20 mm
) on a Shimadzu RID-10A refractive index detector and a Shimadzu LC-6AD liquid chromatograph series pumping system (
Tokyo
, 
Japan
). For column chromatography, silica gel (200–300 mesh, Qingdao Oceanview Chemical Co., Ltd., Qingdao, 
China
), octadecyl silica (50 μm, YMC Co., Ltd., 
Kyoto
, 
Japan
), and Sephadex LH-20 (Pharmacia Company Uppsala, 
Switzerland
) were used for isolation and purification. All chemical reagents were acquired from 
Tianjin
Concord Technology Co., Ltd., (
Tianjin
, 
China
).

Cell viability of NCI–H460 cells was estimated using the MTT assay (

) and cell morphological methods (

). For the MTT assay, NCI–H460 cells were plated in 96-well microplates. The NCI–H460 cells were attached to the wall after 24 h, after which the incubation buffer was removed. The isolated compounds were added to the cells at concentrations of 10.0 μM, 50.0 μM, and 100.0 μM, and then cells were incubated for 48 h. The absorbance of the samples was measured spectrophotometrically at 
490 nm
. Cisplatin was used as the positive control. Microscopy was performed to examine the cell morphology.

Apoptosis detection and cell cycle analysis were performed using flow cytometry. In our study, NCI–H460 cells were plated and cultured in 1640 medium with 10% fetal bovine serum under 5% CO 2 atmosphere at 37 ◦ C. The cells were then treated with or without sprengerinin C ( 19 ) for 48 h, harvested, and attached. At the appointed times, floating cells were collected, washed twice with ice-cold phosphate-buffer saline (PBS), and distributed in 200.0 μL binding buffer. The cells were then cultured with Annexin V/PI at 25 ◦ C for 15 min in the dark. Apoptosis detection was performed using an AV/PI commercial kit following the manufacturer’ s protocol (
). Cell cycle analysis was performed by flow cytometry to evaluate the effects of sprengerinin C ( 19 ). The NCI–H460 cell line was seeded in 6-well plates, harvested at 48 h post-treatment, and fixed with 70% ethanol at 4 ◦ C overnight. Subsequently, after washing cells with ice-cold PBS, they were stained with the cell cycle detection kit. After incubation at 37 ◦ C for 30 min, flow cytometry and FlowJo software were used to analyze the cell cycle (
).
